The introduction?

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Yeah, just so you know.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Okay.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Well, I'm from Cordelia Ukusogwu.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:29.000
I'm born the year 22nd November 1944.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Thank you.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And then of course, born in Anambra in Nigeria,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:44.000
which is part of Africa, West Africa, in the Commonwealth,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
one of the Commonwealth nations.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Do you remember the area that you grew up in?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Do you remember that area that you grew up in?

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Oh yeah, of course.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
What was it like growing up there?

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Well, my town is a cosmopolitan town, well populated and quite civilised.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:37.000
And then it's quite a busy town and it contains one of the largest markets in West Africa.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Yeah, and that is the Omisha market.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Omisha market is quite near.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And the town is situated at the bank of the River Niger,

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:06.000
where of course we have much of this Monk Park and the rest where they actually lived.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And even as of now, we still have that history of where they lived and how they operated

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:29.000
and what they installed in my town, especially missionaries, the Irish missionaries,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:35.000
especially the Catholic and the Protestants.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Did you used to visit that as a child? Did you used to visit the coast and the waters?

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Oh yeah, yeah, yeah. Of course, my mother was a big trader and she was trading in fish,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:05:00.000
fish smoking and then she was doing the fish trading, a trader with the fishermen.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
And I used to go to get the fish and everything.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And then my mum had a stall where she normally sells fish. So I know the area very well.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:20.000
What other things did you do as a child? What ages as well were you talking?

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:28.000
Oh, the age. Well, I will say I grew up in my town.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:40.000
By the time I started going to school, in primary school, my senior sister got married and then took me with her.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So I had to go to another state to live with her. So I wasn't living with my mum and dad.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:55.000
I was living with my senior sister and I was schooling as well in another state, which is not my own state.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.000
But I schooled partially as kindergarten and nursery and primary a little bit halfway.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Primary before I left my hometown to stay in another town with my sister.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:19.000
And then I continued my schooling and then later on I came back home to stay with my mum and dad.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:34.000
My dad was a big fowl. Well, before I was born, my dad was a blacksmith in the town called Fokadous,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
which is the French speaking area in the boat industry.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:47.000
That's where he was a blacksmith in the boat industry in Fokadous.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And I don't know what his name is. It's one of the French countries. I don't know. I'll change his name by now.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So at that time I wasn't born, but when my dad retired from that, he came home and became a farmer and a hunter.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:16.000
A farmer and hunter back home. And he was quite good with his farming.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:25.000
And then eventually as a hunter, he killed a lion. And then because of that, he was hailed a hero.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:31.000
A big hero back home of a hunter killing a lion and everything.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.000
So it was when we grew up that, you know, come to know that.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And apparently if you check with the year I was born, it was almost as post-World War II.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:54.000
I think 1944, post World War II. That was when I was born.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:02.000
So that's why I said, you know, I can remember that vividly.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And then I was called and my mom had so many of us, you know, because we were separated.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:24.000
So I lived with my sister and then when I finished living with my sister, I lived with my aunt, my mother's sister's daughter.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:34.000
And I lived with her as well. So I didn't grow completely from, you know, from childhood to whatever age.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
But I was very close to my mom. So I lived with my aunt.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And then later on I came back home. Then it was when I came back home.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Then I finished my primary school. So I started to go into modern school.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
We had modern school then. It's a secondary school.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
At the beginning of secondary school, but we call it secondary modern school.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Yeah, so I did that. After that, then I went into nursing.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Okay.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:10.000
My nursing career.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
How old were you when you went into nursing?

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.000
I was about fifteen or sixteen. I went into nursing.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:26.000
So what was your favorite memory of your childhood?

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Well, favorite memory of my childhood because I wasn't living in a sport.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:40.000
I was living with my sister and then with my auntie and then with my mom and dad.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:48.000
And then before I left, I went to my nursing education, which I left home.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Because you have to be in a boarding school.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
Yeah.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:04.000
So my life as a child is so divided in that segment.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:14.000
So I wouldn't recall to say this is the time yet. But I lived here, lived here, lived here.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:19.000
So you wouldn't necessarily pick up moments in there that you would say is your favorite or most enjoyable?

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Yeah, but I enjoyed my life, my time back home.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And I had a grandmother who was a staff member and supported me.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And then before I left home, finally.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So what do you think about that childhood and that upbringing?

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:50.000
Is there one or two events that stick inside your mind or is there more in terms of just something special that might have happened?

00:10:50.000 --> 00:11:06.000
Well, I wouldn't say because at that time, you know, young girls' children, you know, you help your mom to help.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
So my mom was still having children then.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:26.000
You help your mom to look after the baby and babies and everything and help out, you know, in sending messages, you know, that you can be able to cope with with your age.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:38.000
So I wouldn't say it was and I would say because I lived with my aunt and it was helping them when they have children.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:49.000
So I was there as a sort of assisting them, you know, like, instead of the.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
I don't know how to go about it.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:04.000
I won't say it's a nursery, but it's like somebody living with her senior sister and helping her out in helping with the baby, carrying the little ones.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
And then, you know, sort of assisting the family child care.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Yeah, family child care.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
I enjoyed that so much.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And yeah, I would like to know about what it was like with your father after the lion as well.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
What was that? Did that change after you gained that status?

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Well, he did, because in my town, heroes are always welcome and they have a group of heroes.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.000
So every year they celebrate their heroism.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:48.000
And they, you know, they wear regalia like, you know, that lion and then they do all their ceremonies, dancing, drumming and dancing.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So we used to enjoy that.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And then my father being a big hunter, we enjoyed them.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:02.000
Every day he goes out, he brings back, you know, where the beds are, you know, the beds are short.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And then we both hunt us using feeding their families, you know.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So I enjoyed it.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And then my father was quite a materialist person.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
I mean, he's, you know, he's what he does.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:31.000
And both from your father there and your mother, was there certain kind of values they were teaching you as well

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
that you carry now too?

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
My mom was a businesswoman.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:48.000
Businesswoman in the sense that, you know, in the moneys she helps us out, sort us out to go to school.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And then when we come back from school, my mom is in the market, in her shed where she's selling her goose.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:04.000
So we, sometimes we go to the market, you know, help her out and then come back to the house, to the home.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And we help our mom so much, you know.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
All of us are very close.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And the way my mom brought the girls up is the way she brought the boys' house passports.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
So we grew up as...

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And fortunately, my mom was the second wife, not the first wife, because my dad had the first wife.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:41.000
And then, you know, those days polygamy was, you know, quite polygamy in the sense of people marrying more than one wife.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:46.000
My father was the only son of his parents.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
So they said, well, because he's the first son, so he married.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And then the first wife only had two or three children.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:03.000
They said, no, you know, because he's a big farmer, he has to have children to help him, you know, in the farm.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
So he married my mom.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
The first wife had about three children, but my mom had twelve.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
Twelve children.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:23.000
So in those days, children matters a lot in those days, because they are the core of the family.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:35.000
The core is they help out in the farm, they help out in all the house responsibilities and cause of care.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:47.000
So how was that explained to you as well in terms of the multiple mothers too, with your father and then obviously your sisters, your brothers and sisters?

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Was that ever explained to you when you were younger?

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:57.000
I think when we were growing up, we were living...

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
First we were living in our own house.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
My mom has her own room.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
The first wife had her own room.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
My dad had his own room.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And there's a common place in the house.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:14.000
So it's a polygamous one, but you never know.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:24.000
But the other children, by the time we grew up, the children of the first wife, they have already grown and they have married.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And then they are the first two.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:37.000
My mother was more of the one taking care of my dad, looking after why the first wife is on her own, because her children has left home.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.000
So we were the younger ones in the family.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Because my mother had more.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:56.000
When you think you can't, you think it's only my mom that is the mother of the family, because we are more in the family than the other one.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:05.000
So we grew up together, in terms of like old siblings.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:11.000
But there was no differentiation of, oh, you're not the son.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
It was so harmoniously.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:20.000
And then from that and growing up, how did you come into the UK?

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Yeah, my coming to the UK was when I finished my nursing.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:34.000
I finished my nursing career with midwifery and nursing.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And I've been working, even during the war in my country, that three years, I was working as a nurse during that wartime.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And it was really hectic. And I was working more in the war front.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:56.000
Yeah, because there was a hospital that we were based.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So we are treating wounded soldiers and taking care of, you know,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:17.000
wounded soldiers. And then, of course, we have our, you know, war effects, you know, where we have to go to the bunker when there is attack and everything.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:25.000
We stay in the bunker. So then we take our patients into the bunkers and we take them out when there is no attack.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:31.000
We're nursing the patients there, the soldiers.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:34.000
What year was this and how old were you as well?

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:47.000
I finished my nursing and midwifery because that was 1960, end of 66 to 67. That was when the war started.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
So like 23?

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Yeah, about 27 years. And then the war finished in three years.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
Okay.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:08.000
And then my two brothers were here in the UK. Then my senior brothers, they were here from my own mom. They were already here.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:17.000
So when one of them had children and their children, once they have their children, they send them back home.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:29.000
And, you know, they were looked after back home. So during the war, they lived with me where I was working during the war for their own safety,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:37.000
for the safety of the children. So I took care of them. And then during the war, we had some, you know, we called them characters.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:48.000
You know, these international aid workers. They supply food and then we distribute.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:20:00.000
And I was, as a midwife then, I was taking care of them. I was doing much of child and health, mother and child health care.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:14.000
You know, as a midwife, you know, giving vaccinations, treating children, babies and their mothers, pregnant mothers and everything.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:29.000
So during that time, those children, I was able to send them back to their parents here through the characters, the characters international aid organization.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:44.000
So that was, the war ended. So when the war ended, I said to my mom and my brothers that are here that I want to come over

00:20:44.000 --> 00:21:00.000
to at least to sort of get relief from the effect of the war and for me to improve my work and continue to pursue my nursing career as well.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
As soon as I came here, I did that as well.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:10.000
What expectations do you have of the UK?

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
Of coming.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
And where was it? Where was your first place you came to the UK?

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:23.000
I came to the UK and in London. I lived in London with my brother, my single brother.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:33.000
Because that's where I, you know, because he was the one that invited me to come. So I came, I lived with him and the family.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:40.000
And that was in East London. East London, yeah, Matonstone.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:44.000
What were your expectations on London before you came?

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Unfortunately, I came at the time when it was real winter.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
Did you know it was going to be winter?

00:21:53.000 --> 00:22:06.000
I know, I know. I came when it was really bad. I came with Lufthansa, is it Lufthansa flight and I landed in the bedroom.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:13.000
And I didn't know a thing. Fortunately, my brother and his wife, they were at work.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:22.000
So they told me to call them when I get to the airport. So at the airport, I gave them the number and then they called them.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:29.000
I spoke to them that I'm now in Heathrow. So they said I should wait there. When they finished work, they would come down to collect me.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:44.000
So that was how I got myself. So I had people to take care of me when I came in. My brother and wife. And I lived with them.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.000
But it was really cold.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:55.000
Then my brother was, they were living in Lettuce and they say the hospital was very close to where they lived.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:06.000
So I just walked to the hospital to say I'm a nurse. I'm a registered nurse back home. I'm a midwife.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:19.000
So they said, okay, they will take me as a nurse. They will take me as a carer, care assistant. I said, okay, that is the rule.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:40.000
So I was taken as a carer. And then from the way I was doing my work as a professional qualified, they saw I was really quite good in what I'm doing.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:50.000
So there were things that, for example, when the doctors or nurses are working, I always like to be there with them.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:58.000
And then I will ask questions. Especially during doctor's rounds. And they will ask questions. And then the students, they will know it.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And then they will say, has anybody got an idea? And I will raise my hand up and I will answer.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:14.000
And then they say, did you say this is a care assistant? And that was how I managed it.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:25.000
They gave me some very tricky assignments to do. Taking the temperature, doing blood pressure, doing all those things that nurses do.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:43.000
And I was recruited as a care assistant. So when I did all this, they felt, especially the doctors, they felt, oh no, this is somebody that knows what she's doing.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:58.000
So they were the ones that helped me out. The organization, the hospital. Then they sent my name to the NMC, that is the Nussela Mipi Free Council.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:08.000
So that they will now recognize my certificates and they'll see what course they can now send me to do. Adaptation course.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:18.000
They sent me to do. So they asked me, do you want to practice the Nussela Mipi? I said, it's made with me. It's made with me, I prefer.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:26.000
So made with me, they can take you to work if you haven't got the myceliary experience.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And if for you to have that myceliary experience, you have to do six months course. And then you'll be subjected to do the myceliary under supervision.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:51.000
So I have to do one year training, first six months and the second six months. At the first six months, I took an exam.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:26:08.000
And then I got through and then did the second one. But unfortunately for me, before I started the training, I got married.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah. That's in London. I got married. So I was able to do the first six months. Then I went to have my baby.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:29.000
After having my baby, I went back again to do the second one. So I was after I qualified then I was recognized to practice as a midwife.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:50.000
Then in the process of the hospital doing all that and I finished, then they now wrote to the NMC, the Nussela Midwifery Council, that being that I've done very well, that they should now recognize my still have training.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:58.000
So that's what I did. So I was recognized and they gave me my certificate to practice both Nussela Midwifery.

